reviewText: I didn't know there was a first part of Gone until I've noted from the beginning the exaggerated extra-careful behavior of Jill (Amanda Seyfried) and some of her flashbacks when she was supposedly kidnapped and had escaped. It is an effective time-passer movie, but something you won't watch again and here is why. To me, the movie appeared quickly made without much story/character developments and details, yet it was quite haunting and tense (something similar you note in Born Identity). What made it look really shallow - is unconvincing police behavior and the culmination when Jill faces the serial killer. For latter, one hour of tense wait time just to end up with this 5-second culmination scene? Excuse me, I know everyone is busy running, but making this the most important part of the movie like literally 5 seconds long - must be a joke! I agree it is interesting to demonstrate how bits by bits, clue by clue, Jill has been discovering the identity of the killer, but, to me that was supposed to precede the grand finale, which I didn't really see in Gone. Unfortunately, I don't feel like watching the unseen 1st part of these series.
summary: It is actually the second part

reviewText: If you get anything from this movie it would be to move to Portland because apparently there you can elude the police every 5 seconds. I've never seen so much ridiculousness out of a movie. I thought the plot was interesting and I think it could've been well-done, however the whole thing was too unrealistic for my taste. As much as I would like to imagine our heroine as a butt-kicking desperado, I feel like if this was real life she would've been stopped immediately. Also found it to be very anti-climatic and was left with a "Was that it?" feeling after it was over. Don't waste the money or the time.

reviewText: The cops in this exploitation thriller are the downfall. They don't believe the girl who claims she was abducted, nor are they interested that her sister has now disappeared, So, she conducts her own vigilante hunt for the bad guy, all the while eluding the dumb cops who are after her because she's got a gun and she's crazy. None of the cops are remotely realistic, nor is the lack of urgency in the whole affair. There are more red herrings here than in a jar of them. The finale is a hoot. Not credible at all. Watch if you like cheap thrillers with shots of sweaty and dirty bound girls writhing in tight t-shirts.

reviewText: Crime thrillers need some degree of believability. So how the police seem to be portrayed as dumb (as usual by Hollywood writers), in not believing a woman who says she escaped from a killer who placed her in a large hole dug in a forested area adjacent to a large city and where several other women were killed and the police perform no forensics such as examining dirt and other organic material; use search dogs or look for a pattern of missing women. They continue to be portrayed as dumb as she escapes multiple times from them pursuing her. It's not as if she's some "Kick-Ass" super person! So what gives? Really fragmented writing with little or no background on anyone from the killer, to the prey, to the newly hired detective who not coincidentally is portrayed as a jerk. Nothing creative in the story - same old victim escapes; is not credible to others; killer wants to finish the job; she finishes him. Acting was very good at being acting like - robotic and bland.

reviewText: This film is primarily a format for leftists to showcase contemporary thought about a supposed moral and, in this case, intellectual and physical superiority of women over men. Amanda Seyfried's (playing Jill) beauty is supposed to enthrall us (and undermine our sound judgment - the film opens with outline of her naked body in shower).In this film Jill is ostensibly (it is not explained) living upon the life insurance benefit provided through the death or her parents, since she lives in a nice home in upscale Portland, Oregon but works red-eye shift as waitress at a coffee shop/restaurant. As introduced to us, her accomplishments include easily beating up a fit-and-trim man in her self-defense class, and outsmarting every single person she encounters throughout this film (usually by lying cleverly), including a bevy of mostly male Portand police detectives. Not explained is why, if she is so smart, she works, while not enjoying it, graveyard shift night after night as a waitress.Men who get a rise out of watching Amanda Seyfried's beauty bounce through this flick, and women who prefer to believe most men are creeps, and who fantasize their own beauty and imagined overwhelming intelligence will slay all life's challenges will enjoy this film. Everyone else, grounded in some measure of reality, will consider time spent watching this production a thorough waste of time.I gave the film three stars because the serial killer suspense is not the worst I've seen (but it is far from high grade).
summary: I am woman, hear me roar
